<subSubSection id="57B365341303FFD90178B30CFB13FC85" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="1F1636BF1303FFD90178B30CFB13FC85" blockId="11.[777,1418,350,852]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
A New World group comprising 15 species (L. Rico-Arce, pers. comm.) that extends from the south-central USA south to Argentina; the highest concentration of species occurs in Mexico. As noted above, molecular data suggest that sect. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD90178B38CFCEEFE24" box="[777,872,478,501]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Filicinae</emphasis>
is a distinct evolutionary lineage. This group was recognised by Britton and Rose as the genus 
<taxonomicName id="D8A94D3C1303FFD90754B3ACFB9FFDE4" authority="(Britton and Rose 1928)" authorityName="Britton and Rose" authorityYear="1928" baseAuthorityName="Britton and Rose" baseAuthorityYear="1928" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acaciella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<taxonomicName id="D8A94D3C1303FFD90754B3ACFA0CFDC4" box="[1317,1418,510,533]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acaciella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD90754B3ACFA0CFDC4" box="[1317,1418,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Acaciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD90161B04CFB97FDE4" author="Britton NL &amp; Rose JN" box="[784,1041,542,565]" journalOrPublisher="Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref10379" refString="Britton NL, Rose JN (1928) ' North American flora. Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" title="North American flora" type="book" year="1928">
Britton and 
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD901E9B04CFB97FDE4" author="Britton NL &amp; Rose JN" box="[920,1041,542,565]" journalOrPublisher="Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref10379" refString="Britton NL, Rose JN (1928) ' North American flora. Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" title="North American flora" type="book" year="1928">
Rose 
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD901A9B04CFB97FDE4" author="Britton NL &amp; Rose JN" box="[984,1041,542,565]" journalOrPublisher="Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref10379" refString="Britton NL, Rose JN (1928) ' North American flora. Vol. 23. ' (The New York Botanical Garden: New York)" title="North American flora" type="book" year="1928">1928</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD906B1B04CFADCFDE4" author="Pedley L" box="[1216,1370,542,565]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the International Group for the Study of Mimosoideae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="123 - 129" part="15" refId="ref12237" refString="Pedley L (1987) In defence of Racosperma. Bulletin of the International Group for the Study of Mimosoideae 15, 123 - 129." title="In defence of Racosperma" type="journal article" year="1987">Pedley (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, the morphological and chemical attributes of sect. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD9075BB06FFA0FFD85" box="[1322,1417,573,596]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Filicinae</emphasis>
suggest that it could well be treated as a distinct genus; a similar view was expressed by Guinet (in 
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD9069FB02FFAF8FD45" author="Maslin BR" box="[1262,1406,637,660]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the International Group for the Study of Mimosoideae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="108 - 118" part="15" refId="ref11518" refString="Maslin BR (1987) Report of discussions at I. G. S. M. meeting no. 6 on the proposal to split Acacia. Bulletin of the International Group for the Study of Mimosoideae 15, 108 - 118." title="Report of discussions at I. G. S. M. meeting" type="journal article" year="1987">Maslin 1987</bibRefCitation>
). Treated as a genus, this group would be called 
<taxonomicName id="D8A94D3C1303FFD9076FB0CFFA04FD65" baseAuthorityName="Britton and Rose" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1310,1410,669,692]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acaciella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD9076FB0CFFA04FD65" box="[1310,1410,669,692]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Acaciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="7B384B4E1303FFD90178B0EFFBC5FD05" author="Robinson J &amp; Harris SA" box="[777,1091,701,724]" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="195 - 222" part="132" refId="ref12430" refString="Robinson J, Harris SA (2000) A plastid DNA phylogeny of the genus Acacia Miller (Acacieae, Leguminosae). Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 132, 195 - 222." title="A plastid DNA phylogeny of the genus Acacia Miller (Acacieae, Leguminosae)" type="journal article" year="2000">Robinson and Harris (2000)</bibRefCitation>
provided the only molecular insight into relationships within the 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD906EAB08FFB7CFD25" box="[1179,1274,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Filicinae</emphasis>
. They found that 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD90135B0AFFCD2FCC5" box="[836,852,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD9011CB0AFFC19FCC5" box="[877,927,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">rosei</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD9019DB0AFFC7AFCC5" box="[1004,1020,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD90664B0AFFB11FCC5" box="[1045,1175,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">chamelensis</emphasis>
had a sister group relationship to 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD901BEB14FFC59FCE5" box="[975,991,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD90671B14FFBE2FCE5" box="[1024,1124,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">tequilana</emphasis>
, with 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD906BCB14FFB5BFCE5" box="[1229,1245,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2DDDEAAD1303FFD9068FB14FFA0FFCE5" box="[1278,1417,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">angustissima</emphasis>
completing the well-supported clade.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="57B365341303FFD90158B13AFB4EFB6E" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1F1636BF1303FFD90158B13AFB4EFB6E" blockId="11.[777,1418,872,1215]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The section may be characterised in the following ways (see 
<tableCitation id="522B03041303FFD9013AB1DAFC2EFC4E" box="[843,936,904,927]" captionStart="Table 4" captionStartId="5.[300,353,638,658]" captionText="Table 4. Distribution of characters considered important in defining major groups within Acacieae (Ingeae included for comparison) See text for further details. Much of the data presented here are derived from information given in Vassal (1981) and Pedley (1986)" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Table 4</tableCitation>
for further details): Trees, shrubs or suffrutescent perennials. Prickles absent. Stipules normally present, never spinose. Leaves bipinnate, with 1–25 pairs of pinnae; leaflets 3–60 pairs, 3–60 mm long. Petiolar glands absent. Inflorescence systems simple, racemose or paniculate; flowers arranged in globular or obloid heads, white-cream colored, 5-merous, drying a pink-brown color. Floral bracts linear, early deciduous. Ovary on gynophore; a nectariferous disk at the base of the ovary. Pods small, chartaceous, dehiscent. Funicle exarillate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
